<font color="#FF0000">PTSD</font><br>
<tt>Sat Mar 15 22:50:55 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Thoughts on PTSD. Their was an interesting article this last<br>
week in the Dallas Morning News. <br><br>
For years I kept hearing about why was that the Vietnam Vets<br>
had all these disorders, when the Vets of WWII had managed<br>
to cope so well? I think I was like most in puzzling over<br>
the syndrome and whether or not it was real or definable.<br>
Of course the latter 70's and 80's got me straight on that<br>
one. That was my period of struggle. Nam tore me up.<br><br>
Well, in the article it addressed 40 or 50 WWII Vets who had<br>
suddenly had to seek help for the syndrome. What was very<br>
interesting was thier own explanations for why they were<br>
addressing the issue at such a late age.<br><br>
Several said retirement had done it. They had immersed<br>
themselves into career, etc. and stayed aloof from even<br>
being close to their own families for generations. Avoiding<br>
the turmoil with heavy drinking while swapping War stories<br>
at the VFW. Retirement brought time. Time for the memories<br>
to haunt them full time. All of them thanked the Vietnam<br>
Vets for their diligence in insisting they had a problem<br>
most folks didn't have. They said the awareness of us Vets<br>
made resources available to them today. That made me feel<br>
like we made another contribution to our country. Some of<br>
those guys lived horrors on a scope beyond imagination.<br><br>
I think we Nam'ers knew all along that such talk as WWII<br>
men didn't suffer as much as us was a bunch of bunk. I know<br>
I personally knew plenty who could barely even stand the<br>
mention of the War as a subject. They always bled just as<br>
hard as any of us.<br><br>
Good article if anyone wants to read it, try the Dallas<br>
Morning News March 10 issue.<br><br>
See Ya, Brothers.
